<TEXT>
the campaign season for local government offices 
in beijing opened with plenty of hoopla the city communist party 
chief shook hands at the main department store 
a brass band played vans with loudspeakers cruised city streets 
and the official xinhua news agency reported volunteers gave out 
1 million pamphlets 
only the candidates were missing 
they are chosen weeks later but there is no suspense for 
voters only members or supporters of the ruling party are 
nominated incumbents who supported last years prodemocracy 
movement already have been purged 
its like taking part in a play performed for the 
communist party a woman voter said on condition of anonymity 
we dont put much value on our voting rights 
for the communists the elections are a deadly serious play the 
basis of their claim to be the peoples choice 
all other officials are appointed in some fashion so chinas 
assertion of democracy rests entirely upon popular elections held 
every three years for the lowestlevel representative bodies 
district peoples congresses in urban areas and county peoples 
congresses in the countryside 
the congresses make no laws and function mainly as conduits for 
passing citizen complaints and ideas to higher levels beijing has 
18 such congresses with a total of 17000 delegates 
other parts of the country held elections in the spring but 
balloting in beijing was delayed until dec 26 the reason given 
was that everyone was too busy getting ready for the asian games 
held in september 
officials also may have wanted to keep the elections from 
coinciding with the anniversary of beijings massive prodemocracy 
demonstrations which the army crushed in june 1989 among other 
things the marchers wanted more say in picking government 
officials 
voters say they have little part even in choosing the local 
congresses god knows how the candidates are chosen the woman 
said 
after the single burst of citywide publicity that opened the 
election season in late october preparations reverted to 
closeddoor committees that take nominations from such official 
groups as the communist youth league and allchina womens 
association 
a group of at least 10 voters can put a candidate forward but 
few do the candidate would be unable to organize publicity 
activities and would have little chance of success 
the law allows two candidates for each seat but voters say 
there usually is just one 
because there are no competing parties television ads or 
debates campaigns are placid events it is not mandatory to vote 
but failure to do so is frowned upon and would be noticed 
chinese officials insist the system is more democratic than 
multiparty elections in the west which they say keeps power in the 
hands of the rich 
our election rights may not be the same as in the west but 
equality is a basic principle xu jingyu chairman of the 
election commission in beijings chaoyang district said in an 
interview 
he acknowleged not everyone can run for office only those with 
correct ideological views but said this was in keeping with the 
constitution 
delegates have to be able to represent the views of the 
masses he said how can someone who opposes the partys four 
basic principles do that 
the emphasis on ideological correctness is especially strong 
this year in keeping with the countrys conservative turn after 
the democracy movement was crushed 
a public notice addressed to comrade voters in the chaoyang 
district called for vigilence against bourgeois liberals who 
might seek to sabotage the election there have been no reports of 
any such plots 
bourgeois liberals are people who favor westernstyle 
democracy with more than one party 
xu was unable to explain why some people accused of being 
bourgeois liberals were elected to past peoples congresses 
the most prominent example is astrophysicist fang lizhis wife 
li shuxian a physics teacher at beijing university who shares her 
husbands dissident views and was elected in 1987 
she was expelled from the haidian district peoples congress in 
1989 soon after police accused her and fang of 
counterrevolutionary crimes they since have been allowed to go to 
the west 
people change xu said maybe when she was elected she 
didnt have this problem 
</TEXT>
