<TEXT>
here are excerpts from the opening statement 
of edwin j gray former chairman of the federal home loan bank 
board at mondays session of the senate ethics committee 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
near the beginning of this drama in march of 1984 charles 
keatings american continental corp bought lincoln savings a 
california statechartered sampl california law then permitted 
direct equity investments mr keatings sampl could buy companies 
and stocks participate in leveraged buyouts build and run hotels 
and own and operate real estate development ventures of all types 
mr keating could easily raise the funds he needed to do such 
things because lincoln savings with its federally insured 
deposits was a cash cow well able to finance these endeavors 
in 1984 mr keating in order to gain permission to acquire 
lincoln had assured state regulators and us that he would continue 
to operate the institution as primarily a home mortgage lender 
despite these assurances he soon began using californias 
liberal thrift laws to their fullest one month after mr keating 
acquired lincoln the bank board asked congress to roll back state 
thrift powers to the boundaries set by the garnst germain act for 
federally chartered thrifts thats something congress had done for 
federally chartered thrifts 
this move would have severely curtailed direct investment 
authority for california thrifts but the bank boards request went 
nowhere the board began trying through administrative 
rulemaking to limit the investment authority granted by 
california law and mr keating enlisted the first wave of paid 
apologists dedicated to preventing us from doing so all of this 
occurred before i had even heard of charles keating 
the bank board adopted its first directed direct investment 
regulation on january 30 of 1985 it limited the amount of a 
thrifts assets that could go into direct equity investment to 10 
percent of assets unless regulators permitted exceptions and to 
be granted only under specific conditions 
by the time of our rulemaking mr keating had apparently been 
lobbying heavily to try to insure that the rule wouldnt be applied 
against lincoln or that it would be scuttled by a powerful show of 
force in congress largely as a result of the keating effort more 
than half the members of the house signed a resolution intended to 
cause me and my colleagues to back down in the face of this 
demonstration of power we didnt and the direct investment 
regulation stood 
mr keating next sought to deal with this problem by hiring me 
out of my job as his chief regulator he did so in a personal 
meeting with my chief of staff who on my prior instructions 
rejected his proposal 
in 1986 it became clear that mr keating was conducting a 
campaign through its employees agents and sympathizers to create 
the impression with the media and with other influence molders 
that i was feuding with him actually ive never met him or even 
seen him in person but we began hearing and then reading that i 
was somehow conducting a vendetta against lincoln 
a graykeating feud story ran on the front page of the 
washington post on september 20th 1986 in which it also was 
falsely alleged that i was harassing lincoln from that time 
forward my senior staff and i believe that the alleged gray 
vendetta was intended to be used by keating as a basis for fighting 
thrift regulators in the future 
vendetta accusations were not the only pressure tactics i saw in 
operation that year it was we now know not an accident that 
opposition to my efforts to warn about growing sampl problems 
coincided with the appearance of critical news stories about 
certain of the bank boards practices 
when i arrived at the agency these practices had been in place 
for over a decade the regional banks would routinely pay part of 
the expenses incurred by bank board officials including myself 
when we attended outoftown conferences of the regional banks 
these practices had been approved by bank board counsel on more 
than one occasion and were known to the congress 
despite this history and whatever may have been the source or 
motivation of the news stories i concluded that the questions 
raised in the news stories were not unreasonable and that the 
public perceptions created by the news stories were not only 
hurting me but would even if i survived in office destroy any 
chance i might have at reforming the thrift system 
i therefore reviewed these practices revised them and without 
being required or asked to do so paid back certain challenged 
expenses i also reimbursed the cost of airplane charter arranged 
for me by regional bank officials on the occasion of a severe 
medical emergency in my family the total amount of the 
reimbursements were approximately 27000 
this matter was thoroughly investigated by the office of 
government ethics the department of justice and the bank boards 
inspector general none of whom recommended any remedial action 
against me these attacks were part of a pattern of pressures meant 
to discredit and to discredit me and derail the effort to 
achieve sampl reform and protect the american taxpayers 
senator cranstons opening statement signaled that some would 
like this issue to play the same role at these hearings i hope it 
will not 
in mid1986 the terms of my two bank board colleagues mary 
grigsby and donald hovde were due to expire news reports 
speculated as early as august 1986 that two keating associates 
professor george benston of the university of rochester a paid 
consultant to lincoln since 1984 and lee henkel a keating lawyer 
and close associate who also was a major borrower of lincolns 
were being seriously considered by the white house under the 
leadership of donald regan to fill the grigsby and hovde seats on 
the bank board 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901127-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
henkel was indeed given a recess appointment for the republican 
slot on the bank board in late october of 1986 this sent a very 
strong signal to me and the bank board staff that mr keating had 
especially heavy political clout and that he intended to use it 
the pressures during those years came from the hill as well as 
the executive branch and the media and the congressional 
pressures were the heaviest of all 
beginning in 1985 id been asking congress for a major 
recapitalization of the fslic the federal savings and loan 
insurance corp that was in october of 1985 finally in the 
fall of 1986 we had a recapitalization bill moving through 
congress inadequate as it was but suddenly it stopped 
incoming speaker james wright had been told that our 
regulators were being too tough on texas sampls owned by his 
constituents and contributors and he personally was putting a hold 
on the bill until he could get some satisfaction 
the delay was critical it also impressed on all of us at the 
bank board if we had not known it before that congressional 
consent was the key to stopping the hemorrhage the losses to the 
taxpayers 
board member henkel in his first open meeting of the bank board 
proposed an alternative regulation for our direct investment rule 
which was due to expire his version would have forgiven thrifts 
for certain massive violations of the grandfathering clause of the 
extant direct investment regulation 
we believed then and i believe today that mr henkels 
regulation was specifically intended to benefit lincoln and only 
lincoln savings 
newly appointed board member larry white and i voted against 
henkels regulation and for renewing our direct investment rule 
later at the end of february of 1987 mr white and i voted to 
strengthen the direct investment regulation very substantially by 
tying a thrifts ability to make some equity investments to the 
level of tangible net worth on the books of the institution 
lincoln savings thereupon sued the bank board on the grounds that 
we had exceeded our statutory authority 
on april 2nd 1987 this issue of the direct investment rule 
came up in my meeting with senators deconcini mccain cranston and 
glenn as to which ive already testified in my deposition today 
as we look back it is clear many times over that the lions share 
of the staggering losses that taxpayers will have to pay are the 
result of overly rapid deposit growth fueled in large part by 
money brokers which went into equity investments particularly 
those involving speculative real estate projects 
charles keatings losses from direct investments and highrisk 
land loans demonstrate beyond doubt that our regulatory concerns 
our warnings and our actions were correct charles keatings 
purpose for lincoln savings was to use the institution as a source 
of funds for enterprises that had nothing to do with making home 
mortgages available to those seeking the american dream 
but there were many other thrift managements which to a lesser 
or greater extent were operating their thrifts for similar ends 
lincoln was not at all unique 
these people played their political cards like masters in order 
to keep the regulators at bay all the time the stakes for the 
taxpayers continued to go up and up and up 
the technique did not intimidate me or my regulators im proud 
to say but it visited a crushing burden on both the taxpayers and 
those depositors and bond holders who had placed their trust in our 
regulatory system 
i hope this account makes clear that when i met in 1987 with 
the five senators now before this committee we were not discussing 
a normal regulatory issue to be addressed through the normal kinds 
of pressure negotiation and compromise this was a matter of clear 
and present danger to the nation and demanded a more sober 
treatment 
we have heard a lot in these hearings about the responsibility 
of senators to represent constituent interests but ive always 
assumed that we also send our senators to washington because we 
think they will have the sense to know when narrow constituent 
demands must take a back seat to the safety of their constituents 
as a whole 
i hope this recounting of events also makes clear that when i 
met with the five senators it was not in the midst of a normal 
political climate these meetings capped years of private threats 
and public vilification designed not just to change particular 
decisions by the bank board but to render us unable to carry out 
our central responsibilities to protect the financial system and 
the taxpayers from loss no one in washington with the slightest 
knowledge of this issue can have been ignorant of this situation or 
the effect that it would have on the way regulators received and 
interpreted messages from senators and congressmen 
finally i hope my experience makes clear that the savings and 
loan problem was not merely a problem of personal ethics among five 
senators there were hundreds of players in this political drama 
each of whom had some sort of interest in preserving the existing 
system rather than changing it and reforming it and making it 
safer and more sound 
this is the classic problem of a democracy the private 
interests fit together so closely and operate so powerfully that 
the public interest the broad public interest the ordinary 
folks out there their interest never gets served perhaps this 
crisis will encourage all of us to build more safeguards against 
that danger in the future 
thank you 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901127-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
hafr albatin saudi arabia ap around the dinner table under 
a bedouin tent the foreign legionnaires sang of their love for the 
desert and readiness to die for france 
the deserts for us as for sailors the sea they roared 
let the sun bronze our corpses 
the 1100 men of the 2nd infantry regiment deployed in the 
northeastern saudi arabian desert come from 46 countries some 
joined to flee legal problems or broken love affairs and nearly 
twothirds use an assumed name 
we never ask them why they joined the foreign legion said 
lt col antoine lecerf 40 
their past is their property maybe theyre looking for 
adventure maybe they want to forget something in their own life 
we dont mind 
americans may complain of harsh conditions waiting out saddam 
hussein in the desert but thats not something thats heard at the 
legion camp 65 miles south of the border with iraqioccupied 
kuwait 
the legion was almost born in the desert said cpl martin 
meyer 28 of chicago we love it out here 
the 2nd infantry is part of the frances 4000man rapid action 
force deployed alongside arab troops in the faceoff with saddam 
the legionnaires have seen action in lebanon chad gabon and 
other hotspots where they were sent to advance frances foreign 
policy 
far from shunning a fight the legionnaires look forward to it 
five years without seeing combat and im still a virgin 
said meyer who joined after serving in the us air force 
thats what i signed up for thats what everyone signed up 
for 
he said he preferred the legion to the us military because 
its a lot more liberal hey i got my corporals stripes because 
i was thrown in the nick jail they dont like wimps 
as they wait for action the legionnaires live with gallic 
savoirfaire 
they have bought large bedouin tents and arab carpets to lay on 
the sand they drink from glasses decorated with the regimental 
crest and the food is a far cry from the american mres or meals 
ready to eat that the gis complain about 
in the event of hostilities they have packaged readytowarm 
rations but those too are a lot different from american army 
chow one such ration includes lamb with beans mushroom soup 
beef conserve tunnyfish in oil candy caramels and a variety of 
other goodies 
the desert is their home 
its very beautiful lecerf said you can have a constant 
communion with nature i love the desert because its a demanding 
environment that imposes a special effort from everyone 
cut off from their backgrounds the legionnaires can find a new 
life among their comrades with no questions asked 
most of my friends are in jail or dead so it was a good 
move to sign up said pvt john garcia 20 of the bronx new 
york he stressed it was his real name and that im no 
criminal 
asked whether he was hoping for war he answered in his newly 
learned french yes of course everyone here is 
the legionnaires have strips of velcro on their uniforms for 
name tags but none of the men of the 2nd infantry wore the tags 
many refused to be photographed or to give their names even 
aliases 
these days many of the new recruits come from eastern europe 
the legion predicts that eastern europeans will form the largest 
minority within two years 
it ethos hasnt changed much since the 1939 movie beau geste 
starring gary cooper told the story of three wellborn brothers who 
join the legion to escape disgrace 
capt hans eberle a 25yearold legion veteran said 
legionnaires are like modeling clay they have to adapt 
speaking french in an accent tinged with his native german and 
the lilting southern accent of the legions home base nimes 
eberle acknowledged he misses his wife and three children 
but in our noble profession there are so many rewards said 
the 44yearold captain who has made hundreds of parachute jumps 
with a full combat load 
the legionnaires spend up to 300 days a year away from home base 
in a totally masculine world and they shudder at the thought that 
women could ever be recruited 
i love women too much to accept that they be in the legion 
said eberle ive seen the corpses of women its not a pretty 
sight 
as reporters left the legion camp eberle said goodbye see 
you in baghdad 
