a man accused of shooting his exwife in 
the head and murdering her lover was set free after two trials in 
which the defense argued the womans memory was faulty because of 
her head wound 
george gurney who had spent 17 months in jail became a free 
man monday after his second trial in five months ended in a hung 
jury 
the prosecution decided against a third trial citing the health 
of gurneys former wife miriam stoltzgurney she spent four 
months recovering from the february 1989 attack before identifying 
gurney as the assailant 
bringing her back getting her ready for trial and actually 
subjecting her to having to testify again not only is not helping 
her rehabilitation process its inhibiting that process said 
assistant attorney general michael ramsdell 
the defense had hammered at the reliability of stoltzgurneys 
memory calling a harvard university psychologist who testified 
that people with her type of head injury sometimes create memories 
to fill in gaps in their recall 
defense attorneys also stressed that there was no physical 
evidence linking gurney 54 to the crime scene 
gurney who did not testify had no comment monday 
stoltzgurney 49 was not present for the dismissal of the case 
the jury deadlocked last week after deliberating about 14 hours 
according to one juror who spoke on condition of anonymity the 
dissenting juror doubted stoltzgurneys testimony the first trial 
ended in a 66 deadlock in june 
gurney was charged with murder attempted murder and kidnapping 
