<TEXT>
education secretary lauro cavazos is calling 
on colleges and universities to make tough choices to cut 
costs 
cavazos insisted monday that colleges still are affordable 
although tuition increases during the 1980s averaged about 8 
percent a year average tuition and fees for fall 1990 ranged from 
884 at twoyear public colleges to 9391 at fouryear private 
colleges 
escalating costs of higher education have some analysts 
predicting that four years of college early in the next century 
may cost several hundred thousand dollars said cavazos 
cavazos stressed that the predictions are based on 
misperceptions about both the true cost of college and the 
availability of student financial aid yet he released a 
handbook entitled tough choices to help colleges examine 
institutional goals and priorities and make decisions to control 
spending 
if we are to keep higher education affordable colleges and 
universities are going to have to make serious efforts to control 
costs he told reporters each institution must identify its 
central mission and focus and then allocate resources accordingly 
with the understanding that no single institution can do everything 
well 
for example cavazos said colleges should consider merging 
duplicative services or programs and possibly eliminating programs 
including certain athletic or sports programs institutions also 
might consider coordinating services with nearby schools he said 
 
 
