<TEXT>
voters who have over the past year cast 
ballots in eastern europes first free elections in decades were 
sometimes able to get the results from the evening news thanks to 
a german polling firm 
the bonnbased infas polling institute has made one of the first 
major injections of technical skill into eastern europe in the form 
of exit polls 
the institute founded in 1958 has done exit polling in 
elections in former east germany romania czechoslovakia bulgaria 
and poland 
in poland on sunday infas was within a few percentage points of 
the final result just hours after the polls closed 
it is yet another indication of the might a united germany will 
have in eastern europe as countries lacking in many of the basic 
skills of democracy turn to their nearest and most powerful 
democratic neighbor 
germany is the chief provider of aid to eastern europe and 
major german companies have through years of cultivating contacts 
established themselves firmly in the countries of the former soviet 
bloc 
freed by eastern europes reforms and prompted by their 
fledgling medias attempt to cope the eastern european polling 
ventures mark the first time infas has conducted election polls 
outside germany officials said 
initial exit polls from infas which was hired by polands state 
television projected that lech walesa would take 41 percent of the 
vote with prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki and emigre stanislaw 
tyminski tied at 205 percent 
further infas results released around midnight from the 404 
districts it targeted gave walesa 393 percent tyminski 232 
percent and mazowiecki 199 percent 
based on complete but unofficial returns released by the 
polish news agency pap on monday walesa won 3996 percent of the 
vote tyminski 2310 percent and mazowiecki 1808 percent 
these first projected results are sometimes 2 or 3 percentage 
points away from the final result but the second projected result 
is much closer reinhart schneider one of the project leaders in 
infas election department said in an interview monday 
infas has been very accurate in its forecasts schneider 
said he was especially proud of results from romania the most 
difficult of the institutes foreign ventures 
romania was really a unique situation it was a revolutionary 
situation still he said 
but he added you can see how close the methods come 
in the may 20 presidential elections ion iliescu of the 
national salvation front received 851 percent of the vote and 
radu campeanu of the national liberal party got 102 percent 
according to final results 
exit poll projections gave 83 percent of the vote to iliescu and 
11 percent to campeanu schneider said 
infas has been approached and paid by the media in the country 
holding each of the elections schneider said in each case it 
hooked up with a partner institute that translated the institutes 
questions and provided native speakers to do the interviewing 
this is not very difficult but you have to have the 
experience to do this schneider said these eastern countries 
have not yet the experience in doing these things because they have 
not had democratic elections for years for decades 
