arbitrarily harass homeless and poor people said doug lasdon an 
attorney from the legal action center for the homeless 
without comment the supreme court monday declined to review the 
case lasdons group had asked it to hear the group argued the ban 
infringes on freespeech rights 
transit officials praised the high courts refusal to review the 
ban saying it will help restore order underground 
nobody likes to push around poor people said jared lebow a 
spokesman for the transit authority which runs the nations 
largest subway system with 35 million daily riders but we also 
recognize that our obligation is to people who use the system to 
get to and from work 
the ban was imposed in october 1989 the objective was to crack 
down on vagrancy in subways where many of the citys estimated 
80000 homeless people go to stay warm sleep and beg for small 
change 
no fine is imposed beggars are merely removed or directed to a 
service agency for help 
