<TEXT>
selffunded employee health care plans which 
cover some 95 million working americans are not subject to state 
insurance laws and regulations the supreme court ruled today 
the court by a 71 vote said in the case of a seriously 
injured pennsylvania teenage girl that federal regulation of such 
plans preempts any state regulation 
selffunded plans are those in which all benefits are paid 
directly by an employer and not purchased through an independent 
insurance company 
in an opinion by justice sandra day oconnor the court said 
such health care plans are governed by the federal employee 
retirement income security act of 1974 erisa 
in view of congress clear intent to exempt from direct state 
insurance regulation erisa employee benefit plans we hold that 
erisa preempts pennsylvania law oconnor wrote 
justice john paul stevens was the sole dissenter justice david 
h souter who joined the court after the case was argued last 
month did not participate in the decision 
the illinoisbased fmc corp has a selffunded plan for its 
employees and their dependents and that plan paid for a 
substantial part of the more than 178000 in medical expenses 
incurred by cynthia ann holliday since a january 1987 automobile 
accident in indiana county pa 
miss holliday then 15 suffered permanent injuries when the car 
in which she was a passenger crashed 
her father gerald is an fmc employee 
holliday sued the cars driver robert lyons in state court 
under a settlement miss hollidays financial recovery was limited 
to 4987550 plus interest 
when fmc sought to recover some of its expenses by claiming the 
lawsuit settlement funds holliday successfully invoked a 
pennsylvania law that prohibits such action 
fmc then turned to a federal trial judge for help contending 
that the federal law erisa was meant to be the sole means of 
regulating its health care plan and that it therefore preempted 
the prohibitive pennsylvania law 
the trial judge and the 3rd us circuit court of appeals 
ruled against fmc 
but todays decision reversed the lower court rulings saying 
fmc was right in its contention that the federal law superseded any 
state regulation 
the justices sent the case back to the lower courts where 
presumably fmc will be able to recover the money miss holliday won 
in the lawsuit against lyons 
fmcs appeal to the nations highest court has been supported by 
the us chamber of commerce the selfinsurance institute of 
america and numerous selffunded health and welfare plans 
the case is fmc corp vs holliday 891048 
</TEXT>
