a federal appeals court today refused to 
reconsider its decision setting aside former white house aide 
oliver l norths three felony irancontra convictions 
the us circuit court of appeals denied a petition by 
independent counsel lawrence e walsh that the 12member court 
rehear the case decided july 20 by a split threejudge panel 
the decision sends the case back to us district judge gerhard 
a gesell who must hold a hearing to determine if the 1987 
testimony north gave congress under a limited grant of immunity 
from prosecution had unfairly seeped into the trial 
walsh probably will appeal todays decision to the supreme 
court an action that would delay the lower court hearing if the 
justices agree to consider the case 
walsh issued a statement today saying we appreciate the 
extended consideration that was given to our petition for 
rehearing we are studying the opinions and in all probability will 
petition the supreme court because of the importance of the 
questions involved 
in its july 20 decision the threejudge panel set aside the 
three convictions pending such a hearing by gesell it also 
reversed outright one of the convictions ruling that gesell had 
given improper jury instructions on two points 
north was convicted of helping to prepare a false chronology of 
the irancontra affair for congress altering or destroying 
national security council documents and accepting an illegal 
gratuity the installation of a security fence outside his home 
gesell placed the retired marine lieutenant colonel on 
probation fined him 150000 and ordered him to perform 1200 
hours of community service 
the appeals court did not indicate how its members voted on 
whether to rehear the case though two judges did not participate 
for undisclosed reasons seven votes are needed for the full court 
to rehear a case already decided by a threejudge panel 
in a separate order the threejudge panel reaffirmed all but 
one section of its july 20 opinion the change did not affect the 
outcome of the 21 decision which drew a dissent at the time from 
chief judge patricia wald 
the panel withdrew a section of its july 20 opinion stating that 
gesell had improperly instructed the jury on how to reach a 
unanimous verdict on the count involving destruction of documents 
the panel admitted that it had misread the trial record and 
found that gesell had given a proper instruction on reaching a 
unanimous verdict on that count 
but the panel again over walds dissent stuck by its earlier 
decision that gesell had improperly told the jury to ignore 
evidence that north thought he was acting with authority of his 
superiors in the reagan administration when he altered or destroyed 
documents 
judge ruth b ginsburg dissented from the full courts refusal 
to reconsider this question 
a majority of the panel held that a government official may 
not be convicted of altering concealing or shredding official 
documents if he believed however unreasonably that his actions 
were legal ginsburg wrote of the july decision by circuit judges 
laurence silberman and david sentelle two appointees of president 
reagan 
a federal grand jury still is investigating the roles of other 
reagan administration officials in the irancontra affair north 
has used the july 20 decision as a basis for refusing to testify 
before that panel he had been questioned several times by the 
grand jury before that decision 
