<TEXT>
when the taxman calls everyone must answer 
even the state 
the states top court ruled tuesday that state government is not 
exempt from a law that requires taxpayers to pay their property tax 
even while theyre appealing the assessment 
the state must pay its local property taxes when they are 
due court of appeals judge vito titone wrote in the unanimous 
decision 
state officials launched the case on behalf of the hudson 
riverblack river regulating district in 1987 fulton county 
raised the states tax bill for 380 pieces of property operated by 
the district in northampton from 234000 to 440000 according to 
the attorney generals office 
state lawyers argued that laws that protect new york state from 
paying penalties for delinquent taxes and from tax foreclosure also 
exempted it from paying taxes pending resolution of its appeal of 
the assessment 
but titone argued that if anything the existence of those two 
specific exemptions indicate lawmakers want the state to be treated 
like any other taxpayer when it comes to an appeal 
indeed the balance of equities may even tilt more heavily in 
favor of local governments taxing power when the state is the 
taxpayer since the state is generally in a better position than an 
individual taxpayer to absorb a temporary overpayment pending 
judicial correction titone said 
