<TEXT>
goodbye pricey menus long lines and goat 
cheese hello bistros broccoli and service with a smile 
todays gloomy economy is having a big impact on dining out 
but its not all bad according to the 1991 zagat new york city 
restaurant survey 
consumers are demanding and getting more for their money now 
even on tighter budgets and stricter expense accounts than they 
did a few years ago said tim zagat publisher and editor of the 
pocketsized guide which arrives at bookstores this week 
restaurateurs are holding down prices throwing in more extras 
like free appetizers and larger portions and working harder to 
keep customers happy he says 
according to zagat survey which publishes the restaurant guide 
the number of restaurant closings rose from 38 in 1989 to 54 in 
1990 but the number of openings held at 125 
the new eateries generally have a casual atmosphere lower 
prices and simple food such as scaleddown bistro regional 
american or pasta fare according to the survey 
huberts a fancy upper east side restaurant was among the 
recent closings it tried to change with the times shedding its 
luxury image and slashing its prices to 100 for a dinner for two 
but along the way the establishment lost direction according 
to the guide 
diners may be less willing to support certain kinds of 
marginal or expense account hangouts zagat said but theyre 
still trying out new places in great numbers and are proving 
especially supportive of smaller neighborhood places with moderate 
prices and simpler food 
a total of 5500 volunteer diners participated in the 1991 zagat 
survey which reviewed the decor food and service at 1012 
restaurants citywide to accommodate the shift to dollarwise 
dining the guide for the first time includes a bang for the 
buck index of 100 goodvalue restaurants 
it costs more to get a full tank of gas than to get a good 
meal out in new york zagat said 
still new york citys highpriced restaurants are the highest 
by far in the country according to the survey the average price 
for dinner at the citys 20 most expensive restaurants is 6707 
in washington the average is 5023 los angeles 4822 san 
francisco 4808 baltimore 3830 atlanta 3744 new orleans 
3464 seattle 3395 st louis 3323 and kansas city 2523 
at the top end of the scale in new york the survey notes there 
are still tremendously successful establishments the four seasons 
where dinner averages 64 and lutece where dinner averages 71 
are rated as the most popular 
bouley which opened less than two months before the october 
1987 stock market crash was rated as having the best food in the 
city the ninecourse tasting menu at the flowerfilled french 
restaurant is 65 
it proves that cinderella stories are still possible among new 
york restaurants and that put to the wall some places are 
performing at the peak of their game zagat said 
