<TEXT>
polands defense minister said tuesday he 
is worried about the soviet unions stability and plans to 
strengthen polish troop levels along the two nations frontier 
defense minister piotr kolodziejczyk said polands troop levels 
have been reduced by 100000 to 350000 over the last three years 
and that he expects a further reduction of another 100000 
he said about 40 percent of its armed forces now are along the 
german border and 20 percent on the soviet frontier 
kolodziejczyk said those troops will be redistributed with 
onethird along the soviet border a third along the german border 
and the remainder in the polish interior 
he said the troops are being moved because of lessened eastwest 
tensions and because of worries about the soviet unions stability 
even if the situation in the east soviet union were stable 
the troops would have to be distributed in a different way 
kolodziejczyk said but the situation is not stable which is a 
source of great concern for the polish government 
kolodziejczyk spoke with reporters after meeting with german 
defense minister gerhard stoltenberg 
the soviet union is expected to have an unusually harsh winter 
this year there is serious concern that will touch off famine in a 
crumbling empire already beset by other problems and cause an 
exodus of hungry soviets 
there also has been concern about civil unrest 
germany has begun a huge emergency program to help out the 
soviet union during the winter months 
the german branch of the catholic relief organization caritas 
said tuesday it will begin sending 30000 food packages to the 
soviet union this weekend 
german television said further aid might be airlifted into the 
soviet union 
a highlevel team of economic agricultural and transport 
officials from germany led by chancellor helmut kohls top foreign 
policy adviser traveled to moscow on tuesday to talk with soviet 
officials about organizing emergency assistance 
kohl has stressed in recent days the importance of helping out 
the soviet union and ensuring that soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev can survive the growing economic and political problems 
facing his nation 
after his talks with stoltenberg kolodziejczyk also said poland 
is interested in acquiring armaments once owned by east germany and 
now in the possession of united germanys armed forces 
through unification stoltenbergs ministry has inherited from 
the east germans among other things sovietmade mig29 aircraft 
rated as among the worlds best fighter planes 
