the us attorneys office is considering 
exhuming the unidentified body of a murder victim to see if it is 
that of missing candy heiress helen brach a newspaper reported 
tuesday 
for the past six months federal agents and illinois state 
police detectives have been trying to gather evidence that might 
connect the body with brachs disappearance according to the 
chicago tribune 
hampering the investigation is the fact that the dead woman 
found in the woods in calumet city in 1978 was missing her hands 
and part of her face including her teeth the newspaper said 
citing unidentified sources 
that has made it impossible to compare brachs dental records to 
those of the body 
investigators hope to exhume the body and conduct a series of 
tests including comparison of brachs xrays with those of the 
woman sources told the newspaper monday 
brach heiress to the brach candy co fortune disappeared after 
checking out of the mayo clinic in rochester minn on feb 17 
1977 she was then 65 years old 
the new interest in the body stems from a federal investigation 
here into a number of horse traders suspected of defrauding wealthy 
individuals who purchased horses the tribune said 
one theory is that brach was murdered after she repeatedly 
complained to authorities that she was defrauded in the purchase of 
horses the newspaper said 
at the time of her disappearance her net worth was estimated at 
17 million the value of her estate has increased to more than 50 
million most of her estate has gone to a charitable trust called 
the helen brach foundation 
