<TEXT>
the supreme court was asked tuesday to free a 
rhode island college from having to pay nearly 44000 to a nursing 
student because it kicked her out for being too fat 
outside the debate centered on alleged discrimination against 
fat people 
but inside the court heard 60 minutes of technical legalistic 
arguments pitting salve regina college in newport ri against 
sharon l russell now a nurse in st petersburg fla 
what the justices must decide by july is whether a federal 
appeals court correctly deferred to a federal trial judges 
interpretation of rhode island common law a ruling that such 
deference was warranted will mean ms russells victory is upheld 
but steven snow a providence ri lawyer representing the 
college argued tuesday that the appeals court should have rendered 
its own interpretation of state common law rather than defer to the 
trial judge 
his contention drew numerous probing questions especially from 
justices sandra day oconnor john paul stevens and byron r white 
at one point oconnor noted that most federal appeals courts 
have shown trial judges the same deference when considering state 
law issues that land in federal court 
edward t hogan the east providence ri lawyer for ms 
russell argued that forcing appeals courts to engage in the type 
of review snow suggested would result in a waste of time 
ms russell who has become a champion in the fight against size 
discrimination weighed over 300 pounds when dismissed from salve 
regina in 1985 
she had entered the coed catholic school three years previously 
and received excellent grades through her freshman and sophomore 
years but after beginning her nursing studies ms russell was 
told by faculty members her weight concerned them 
after being dismissed ms russell transferred to another school 
