<TEXT>
growth in world trade is unlikely to be seriously 
affected by the conflict in the persian gulf according to a report 
from the general agreement on tariffs and trade 
industrialized countries are now better able to cope with high 
energy prices than during the last oil shock according to the 
report from the secretariat of the 100nation trade forum 
economic activity is less dependent on energy than in the 
1970s the inflation rate is less than half what it was in 1979 
and policymakers have learned the lesson that monetary 
accommodation of a real price shock has persistent inflationary 
effects it said 
the report released wednesday pointed out that current crude 
oil prices of 30 to 35 a barrel were lower than the peak of 1981 
when crude reached the equivalent of 50 a barrel 
while the general situation remains highly uncertain gatts 
economists believe that the growth in the volume of world trade in 
1990 is unlikely to be seriously affected by the gulf crisis it 
said 
the report estimated the volume of world merchandise exports 
will expand 6 percent this year down from a 7 percent increase in 
1989 
but the report warned that third world countries highly 
indebted nations and eastern european economies would be hit 
hardest by the oil price rises 
the report also said a successful conclusion next month of the 
uruguay round of trade talks would likely create a stronger basis 
for the world economy in the 1990s 
it said competition is the best path to rising living 
standards 
the report made no predictions on what would happen if the 
complex negotiations collapse they are now held up over 
disagreements on the size of cuts in farm subsidies 
the report said the value of world merchandise trade in 1989 
rose 75 percent to a record 31 trillion exports of manufactured 
goods outperformed those of farm products which rose by 4 percent 
in volume and 5 percent in value 
world trade in commercial services like transportation and 
telecommunications rose an estimated 9 percent to 680 billion 
services now account for nearly onefifth the total value of world 
exports 
the report said the volume of world trade in the 1980s rose by 
50 percent while its dollar value increased by threequarters 
</TEXT>
