top administration officials expressed concern 
tuesday over the prospect that a fouryear effort to reform the 
global trading system could end in failure because of a deadlock 
over the issue of farm subsidies 
the socalled uruguay round of talks are scheduled to wind down 
next week in brussels with a marathon bargaining session in which 
trade ministers from 107 nations will attempt to resolve remaining 
disputes 
we must not let the uruguay round fail president bush said 
in a speech in monterrey mexico 
however back in washington other administration officials were 
expressing the belief that unless the european community retreats 
from its current position on farm subsidies the talks could 
collapse 
i came back very pessimistic about the outlook and im still 
pessimistic said agriculture secretary clayton yeutter it 
seems to me the position of the european community is so far from 
that of essentially the rest of the world that i see no way to 
bridge that gap in the few days that remain 
yeutter and us trade representative carla hills recently 
visited european leaders to urge compromises on agricultural issues 
confronting uruguay round negotiators 
the united states is pushing for a 75 percent reduction in 
tradedistorting internal farm supports and a 90 percent cut in 
farm export subsidies over 10 years 
however the european community seeking to protect millions of 
small family farms has only offered to cut internal supports by 30 
percent from a 1986 base a position the united states has termed 
closer to an actual 15 percent cut from current levels and 
completely unacceptable 
japan which wants to continue protecting its domestic farmers 
by banning rice imports is the only country that is at all 
supportive of the ec position yeutter said 
the ec members are belgium denmark france germany greece 
ireland italy luxembourg the netherlands britain spain and 
portugal they have more than 4 times as many farmers as the 
united states in a population about a third larger and the farmers 
are a powerful political force 
another administration official briefing reporters on condition 
