defense minister dmitry yazov on tuesday said 
troops may use force to prevent attacks against soldiers defending 
military installations he also warned that nuclear weapons must 
remain under the control of the central government 
yazovs statements in a nationally televised address gave new 
urgency to tensions in the 15 republics and president mikhail s 
gorbachevs efforts to hold the splintering soviet union together 
they also appeared to be the toughest official reaction yet to 
fears that nuclear weapons could fall into nationalist hands 
illegal actions in a number of republics endanger the 
defense capacity of the country he said after the evening news 
in some republics their own army units are being formed 
voices are heard about handing nuclear weapons over to some 
republics decisions are taken requiring relocation of armed forces 
units including strategic units yazov said 
attempts are made to defame and dishonor officers and 
soldiers and members of their families there are armed assaults 
against military installations he said 
yazov listed eight points including one that said nuclear 
forces must remain under national control and that the president 
has final authority on deployment of troops 
earlier this year a russian republic deputy prime minister 
called for the vast republic to possess its own nuclear weapons 
and some nationalists in the restive southern republics reportedly 
have tried to storm nuclear weapons facilities 
