<TEXT>
switzerlands last bastion of male 
supremacy was swept away tuesday by a supreme court judgment that a 
tiny catholic state must allow women to play an active role in 
politics 
the federal tribunal ruled that appenzellrhodes interior state 
violated swiss sexual equality laws by refusing to let women 
participate in its annual legislative assembly 
it said that beginning now women must be allowed to vote at the 
assembly and all local elections and hence be eligible for 
political office in the enclave in northeastern switzerland 
switzerland is a federation of 23 cantons states joined under 
a federal constitution with large powers of local control retained 
by each canton 
swiss women won the vote at federal level two decades ago 
the unanimous decision by one female and six male judges 
followed three separate complaints from appenzellers of both sexes 
challenging the exclusion of women 
its a huge weight off my mind said one of the 
complainants theres rohner sonderegger after the verdict 
the outdoor legislative assembly known as landsgemeinde dates 
to the middle ages traditionally attended by men carrying swords 
to indicate their voting eligibility the colorful ceremony has the 
last say in local affairs 
foreign tourists flocked to the mountainous state with a 
population of just 13000 last april to witness an overwhelming 
no to a proposal for female suffrage 
