<TEXT>
though you might never guess it from the way 
they are described recessions arent all bad any more than 
michael milken is totally greedy or completely charitable 
recessions put stocks on sale making them available to ew 
buyers they allow housing prices to drop into the range of folks 
who have waited for years to fulfill their dream they tend to 
bring inflation down 
in contrast expansions generally are praised though they 
sometimes lead to inefficient buying and selling practices 
deterioration of quality poor service inflation irresponsible 
borrowing habits and the like 
experience has demonstrated in fact that some of the nations 
worst economic problems were generated by expansions and corrected 
by contractions a dramatic example of which is the nations 
nagging imbalance of trade 
year after year during the long expansion of the 1980s americans 
imported far more than they exported the economy was strong and 
one consequence of that strength was the ability and desire to own 
foreign manufactured goods 
it cost americans jobs and it cost them the ownership of part 
of their country since the dollars sent abroad were sent back by 
foreigners to buy american companies and commercial real estate 
now that problem is being addressed thanks to the slowdown and 
the threat of recession americans are watching their dollars they 
are importing less and faced with a domestic downturn domestic 
businesses have improved exports 
despite sharply higher prices for imported oil overall imports 
fell 24 percent in september meanwhile exports have been rising 
if you exclude oil the deficit rate has been nearly halved since 
1987 when the economy faltered 
this corrective ability seldom wins accolades for recessions 
just as bad colds that force overactive people to bed are usually 
damned for the postnasal drip rather than praised for the enforced 
rest that avoids a worse breakdown 
recessions it is true inevitably mean layoffs plant closings 
lowered profits dividend cuts and lowered tax revenues they can 
cause a great deal of pain to a great many people especially if 
they persist for a year or more 
they seldom do since world war ii there have been eight 
economic recessions but only two lasted more than a year from 
november 1973 through march 1974 and from july 1981 through 
november 1982 the recession of 1980 lasted a mere seven months 
and that of 19571958 just nine months two lasted 11 months and 
two persisted for a year 
but in each instance they also set the stage for healthier 
economic expansion reflected in job creation new plants higher 
profits better real wages stronger securities and revenue 
increases 
they rearranged the competitive marketplace routing out poor 
products and poorly managed companies encouraging competition 
creativity and improved productivity and discouraging waste of 
human resources money time and opportunity 
to an extent they routed out frivolous activities and 
expenditures and reestablished more sensible priorities 
all recessions hurt but they also give opportunity to prudent 
folks who saved their money to buy a house or who seek a good 
investment and they offer relief to the millions of people whose 
variablerate loans had become onerous 
a recession will always be viewed as an unwelcome guest or even 
as the enemy who seeks to do us in but the real rascal is the 
excess produced by the preceding expansion recessions seek to 
correct those problems 
in that sense recessions are really the launching pads for the 
good days to follow 
</TEXT>
