the curatolas owned a fixerupper with a 
romantic wraparound porch they had a jeepstyle car with the 
requisite two kids in back summer barbecues for friends and 
chirping crickets to serenade them at night 
it was a suburban dream and the new york couple hated it 
we had all these ideals about what we wanted in a home said 
gerry curatola rolling hills and country roads lots of acreage 
it was very romantic but it wasnt reality the suburbs werent 
home 
many middleclass families have chosen to move away from 
manhattan where violence is on the rise and everything else often 
seems in decline but for the curatolas the city was home crime 
dirt noise and all 
the most important element of anywhere you live is time 
together as a family curatola a dentist said recently 
thats the important priority not commuting fixing the house 
doing this or doing that 
curatola and his wife georgia moved back into the city last 
spring after fewer than four years in their westchester county 
dream house they couldnt take the good life any longer 
for every leisurely weekend in their backyard gerry had at 
least 10 new 1hour commutes notched on his briefcase for every 
pleasant morning with her husband georgia endured many long 
lonely afternoons 
i think women in particular are very affected by a move like 
that said mrs curatola whose young daughter and son provided 
her some relief i dont play tennis and i dont do clubs 
without those suburban mainstays she said the isolation 
sometimes was overwhelming her days were taken up in solitary 
journeys to the market the dry cleaners to her 6yearold 
daughters school 
on the upper west side of manhattan where the couple now lives 
neighbors meet on the elevator standing in line at the bank or at 
the deli theres always something to joke about central park is 
the familys backyard 
the curatolas know the streets are dangerous and that the public 
schools are a mess but they also know fifth avenues christmas 
lights the guggenheim museums art and carnegie halls music 
theres nothing like little italys pasta or the charm of greenwich 
village on a blustery fall day 
the curatolas want their children to experience the citys 
wonderful mishmash of ethnicities and eccentricities the very 
things the mitzners miss 
