<TEXT>
the recording sessions were held in quonset 
huts on movie sets in night clubs after hours some of the 
biggest names in show business from oldtimers like al jolson to 
newcomers like frank sinatra performed 
but the records produced in a sixyear period during and after 
world war ii were heard only by american servicemen overseas now 
through the efforts of a retired navy officer who helped oversee 
their production they are on the us market 
nearly 920 12inch 78rpm records were produced by the army and 
navy from 1943 through 1949 as morale boosters they were called 
vdiscs the records 8 million copies altogether were 
accompanied by 125000 springoperated windup phonographs each 
with 100 steel needles 
they were played on ships in foxholes in trenches on 
airplanes in hospitals said edmond p digiannantonio digi as 
he is known ran the navys part of the program and keeps a 
wellpreserved copy of each record in a closet in his lakeside home 
here 
one serviceman wrote a letter saying he and his buddies were 
playing a vdisc as they headed to the dday invasion of normandy 
digiannantonio said 
the program was started after an army musical branch captain 
named bob vincent suggested to army officials in washington that 
they get popular band leaders like benny goodman and artie shaw to 
record for the troops 
the colonel vincents superior said look these guys dont 
want to hear any swing music or any jazz they want marching 
music digiannantonio recalled 
the colonels reluctance was overcome and we went on to 
include all types of music in all releases said digiannantonio 
from toscanini to spike jones all the way 
when the navy started looking for an officer to run the navy 
marine corps and coast guard part of the program digiannantonio 
was in a hospital in boston recovering from wounds he suffered 
when his ship the heavy cruiser vincennes was sunk off 
guadalcanal 
he had played violin piano and saxophone in high school in 
boston and at massachusetts institute of technology held a 
broadcast engineers license and had recorded shaw glenn miller 
goodman and other band leaders when they came to town 
so he got the job 
along with each box of 20 or 30 records went copies of a 
questionnaire asking the servicemen to say what kind of music they 
wanted white christmas was the most requested piece about 60 
percent wanted jazz or swing 20 percent or so classical and some 
country and western or others marches didnt make it 
some of the music came from movie film tracks and transcriptions 
of radio broadcasts but many were live recordings by artists 
donating their services 
during the early years they were the only records made the 
american federation of musicians at odds with the recording 
companies over royalties had banned all recording until the 
dispute was settled union president james caesar petrillo waived 
the ban to permit the recordings for the troops 
we recorded in night clubs hotel ballrooms movie studios 
quonset huts army bases navy bases wherever the artists were 
said digiannantonio now 73 
in those days when you went on a job you traveled by bus all 
night theyd do a session and wind up at one or two in the 
morning and then come to a studio and lug all the instruments and 
record for us 
the services had tried sending shellac records overseas earlier 
but found that most of them were broken before they arrived the 
vdiscs were recorded on more durable vinylite when vinylite 
became scarce because it was critically needed for insulation they 
switched to formvar a product developed in canada 
instructions on changing needles were often ignored so many of 
the records wore out overseas others were left behind when the war 
ended digiannantonio said that when the vdisc program ended 
officials ordered the remaining disks destroyed to prevent 
commercial use 
nevertheless the library of congress has a nearly complete set 
their quality ranges from very good to poor depending on the 
source said music librarian sam brylawski 
remember how heavy those old needles were said brylawski 
that would gouge a record like a vdisc if we got one from 
someone who really liked their recording a lot it could very well 
be beat up 
digiannantonio took good care of his 
they have been transferred to cassettes and compact discs with 
no adjustment of the original sound 
some people said lets enhance it and do this or this said 
digiannantonio but we said this is the way it was and we are 
going to do it that way 
digiannantonio said he has clearance from the defense department 
to market the recordings and is working with the american 
federation of musicians and broadcast music inc about payment of 
royalties 
he said much of the profit will go to the musicians union 
retirement fund or to the artists their families or their 
estates 
the first installment is a threecassette set with 37 numbers 
including glenn miller playing chattanooga choo choo jolson 
singing mammy and connie boswell crooning good night 
sweetheart 
 
editors note the first vdisk installment is available for 
2495 in cassette or 2995 in compact disc from vdisc po box 
6 springfield va 22150 tollfree telephone 18003233808 
</TEXT>
