<TEXT>
the buyer of us entertainment conglomerate mca 
inc has come a long way since its founder konosuke matsushita 
made japanese home life a bit easier by popularizing the rice 
cooker 
now matsushita electric industrial co ltd has set its sights 
on dominating the promised next generation of electronic 
entertainment highdefinition television with the help of mcas 
rich vault of movies and television shows and studios with which to 
make more 
matsushita pronounced matsoosshtuh needed mca to keep up 
with electronics and entertainment rival sony corp in their 
deadheat battle over the video and hdtv fields analysts say 
the mca buyout is valued at 66 billion compared with the 5 
billion sony paid for columbia pictures entertainment inc last 
year 
unlike sony matsushita is not a household name outside japan 
although its popular brand names panasonic technics and quasar are 
widely known 
matsushita is japans largest home electronics manufacturer and 
thirdlargest corporation with 163 consolidated subsidiaries 
fortune magazine ranked matsushita in 1989 as the 16th biggest 
corporation in the world 
the osakabased company reported holdings of more than 10 
billion in cash alone last year and it earned 148 billion on 
sales of 378 billion 
the influence of legendary founder konosuke matsushita who died 
last year at age 94 is felt in virtually every japanese home where 
an automatic rice cooker takes the drudgery out of preparing the 
nations staple food 
matsushita a man who never went to high school yet became 
japans most famous entrepreneur popularized the electric 
appliance in the 1950s in keeping with his corporate philosophy 
to manufacture items of good quality for daily use in abundant 
supply thereby enriching and improving life for everyone 
that creed in 1932 came less than 15 years after 23yearold 
matsushita left his employer an electric power company to 
capitalize on his own twoway electric socket today the 
matsushita empire has spawned nearly 500 related firms in 37 
countries 
during the 37 years it has operated in the united states 
matsushita has built 12 factories and established seven sales 
companies and a research facility that employ about 10000 people 
matsushitas huge size including its 25000 affiliated 
retailers in japan has proved a disadvantage in switching from 
lowgrowth consumer products which generate 60 percent of its 
sales to more profitable fields 
its inability to produce a new hit product to replace the 
blockbuster video cassette recorder reflects the companys greater 
strength in manufacturing than invention 
seeking to overcome its limitations six years ago matsushita 
launched a longterm plan to focus on seven areas of high 
technology including computers semiconductors and communications 
this year the company invested about 32 billion in liquid 
crystal computer monitor technology computers and semiconductors 
it also is trying to develop profitable movie and television 
cameras for professional use said boris petersik an electronics 
analyst at barclays de zoete wedd securities japan 
so far matsushita has had a hard time cracking sonys dominance 
in the professional video market 
sony also has a head start in the market for entertainment 
software or the movies tv shows and music played in tape 
recorders laserdisc players and vcrs sony achieved this lead 
through its purchase of columbia pictures last year and its 1987 
purchase of cbs records for 2 billion 
the entertainment software market is growing faster than the 
market for the machines that play it most analysts believe that 
control of entertainment software is the key to staying ahead in 
the electronics field 
the mca purchase gives matsushita access to a repository of 
movies and television programs similar to sonys columbia cache to 
be used with the new hdtv format which offers dazzlingly detailed 
images digital sound and wider cinemastyle screen proportions 
with that purchase theres a very good chance theyd get a 
fair share of the hdtv market theyll be glad to have something to 
run on those gadgets petersik says 
