<TEXT>
asias socalled little dragons taiwan hong 
kong south korea and singapore enjoyed explosive growth in the 
80s thanks largely to soaring exports to a thriving american 
market 
but the persian gulf crisis and a looming us recession have 
the region worried because both factors are likely to shave 
economic growth next year analysts say 
still unlike the deep us recession of the early 1980s 
analysts predict those nations should fare better this time around 
because they managed to diversify their export markets 
the us recession surely will be a big blow to taiwans 
economy but we are not as vulnerable this time said wei 
chiling an international trade professor at national taiwan 
university 
so far slackening demand from the united states was cited as a 
major factor behind hong kongs decision to halve its projected 
economic growth rate for this year to 25 percent the united 
states is the british colonys second largest trading partner after 
neighboring china 
softening us demand also is cited for slower growth in 
singapore taiwan and south korea however all three countries 
have predicted growth rates of 6 percent to 8 percent for this year 
and 1991 
although the united states remains among the largest export 
markets for much of the region many asian countries have managed 
to reduce their dependence on us consumer demand for their 
textiles electronics and other goods 
for example 33 percent of taiwans exports were to the united 
states last year compared to nearly 50 percent in 1985 in hong 
kong trade with other countries in the region grew eightfold 
between 1979 and 1989 
japan the economic powerhouse of asia also has been picking up 
the slack in demand created by the sluggish us economy 
the japanese economy is now playing a socalled absorber 
role for the asian neighboring nations although they are 
still dependent on the us market to a great extent said 
nobuyuki ueda senior economist at the longterm credit bank of 
japan 
bangkok bank researcher nimit notapantawart agreed saying the 
diversification strategy may bring only limited benefits he notes 
that many southeast asian countries manufacture similar products 
and will face fierce competition 
also diversifying markets analysts say cannot erase more 
fundamental problems faced by some asian economies among them a 
crisis of confidence in hong kong before it reverts to chinese 
sovereignty in 1997 and the labor unrest and spiralling wages in 
south korea 
elsewhere in asia japans economy is expected to lose some 
steam with most analysts predicting growth of between 4 percent 
and 5 percent next year after four years of roughly 5 percent 
annual growth 
a severe labor shortage the gulf crisis and tighter money 
policies designed to fight inflation are more to blame for japans 
slowdown than lagging exports to the united states experts say 
japans growth is more heavily dependent on domestic demand 
so even if export demand goes down there will not be much 
impact said seiji shinpo head of the overseas research 
department at the governments economic planning agency 
china also might ride out a us recession without major 
disruption analysts say 
although the united states is chinas third largest trading 
partner after japan and hong kong the generally low price of 
chinese manufactured exports could keep the country insulated from 
a recession across the pacific said thomas chan a college 
lecturer specializing in the chinese economy 
chinas low wages also are drawing investment from southeast 
asia 
the asian nation likely to feel the worst economic blow in the 
coming year is the philippines where the government recently cut 
1990 economic growth projections by nearly half to 35 percent 
iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait sent thousands of philippine 
workers home jobless the loss of their foreign exchange 
remittances also depressed the value of the philippine peso and 
higher oil prices triggered a nationwide strike 
