<TEXT>
the supreme court today gave federal energy 
regulators more power to set electricity rates for 49 million homes 
nationwide 
by an 80 vote the justices overturned a ruling that barred the 
federal energy regulatory commission from slashing rate hikes to 
customers in 15 ohio communities 
the court agreeing to do what ferc requested sent the case 
back to a lower court for further study to determine whether the 
ferc orders are just and reasonable 
at issue in todays ruling is the authority shared by ferc and 
the security and exchange commission over public utilities and 
their subsidiaries 
the court said a provision of the federal power act governing 
overlapping authority between ferc and other agencies does not bar 
the energy regulators from seeking to control rates in the ohio 
case 
ferc said it is trying to prevent public utilities from passing 
on to consumers allegedly inflated costs of buying coal and 
possibly other goods and services from the companies subsidiaries 
the bush administration supported an appeal by the ohio 
communities 
the dispute stems from rate hikes first proposed by ohio power 
co in 1982 the utility asked ferc to approve higher rates to 
cover the companys cost of buying coal from its subsidiary the 
southern ohio coal co 
the commission concluded that ohio power from 198286 paid its 
subsidiary between 25 percent and 33 percent more for coal than the 
prevailing market prices 
ferc ordered the utility to refund 134 million to its 
wholesale customers for that period 
but a us circuit court of appeals here which has authority 
over such actions by federal regulators overturned the 
commissions decision last year 
the appeals court interpreted the 1935 federal power act to give 
the sec primary authority to regulate sales contracts between 
holding companies and their subsidiaries 
justice antonin scalia writing for the supreme court today 
said the appeals court was mistaken 
scalia said the case now must go back to the appeals court for 
further study of the ferc orders 
in urging high court review of the case the justice department 
said effective regulation of utilities serving 49 million 
households nationwide could be at stake 
justice david h souter did not take part in the case 
the ohio communities that challenged the appeals court ruling 
most tiny villages are arcadia bloomdale carey cygnet 
deshler greenwich ohio city plymouth republic shiloh 
sycamore wharton bryan st clairsville and wapakoneta 
the case is arcadia vs ohio power co 891283 
