president suharto has warned the 
organization of petroleum exporting countries of a possible oil 
glut if the persian gulf crisis ends mines and energy minster 
ginanjar kartasasmita said tuesday 
suharto called on opec to reapply the quota system to control 
production when the situation has returned to normal in the gulf 
kartasasmita told reporters after a meeting with the president 
we hope and everyone hopes that the gulf crisis will be over 
as soon as possible and we must be ready to cope with the 
difficulty in putting things in order again as it is not easy to 
cut output after enjoying large production kartasasmita said 
he said currently without iraq and kuwait opec produces 226 
million barrels of oil per day exceeding its self imposed quota of 
225 million barrels per day set last july 
iraq and kuwait produced about 4 million barrels per day before 
the gulf crisis that began with the iraqi invasion of kuwait on 
aug 2 the global community immediately boycotted oil from iraq 
and kuwait and some opec nations began producing more than their 
quotas of crude oil to make up for the shortfall 
analysts have said producing nations will be reluctant to cut 
back on the oil they pump once iraqi and kuwaiti crude is put back 
in the marketplace particularly since prices are likely to be 
depressed at that point 
kartasasmita predicted the production may rise further to reach 
23 million barrels per day as demand for opec oil will rise from 
225 million barrels in the third quarter to an estimated 23 
million or 235 million barrels per day in the fourth quarter of 
this year 
indonesia currently produces about 13 million barrels of crude 
oil per day and exports about 780000 barrels 
kartasasmita said the country will raise its output to 14 
million barrels per day next month 
