<TEXT>
one giant economy stretching from above the 
snowy arctic circle to below the sunbaked yucatan peninsula 
thats the dream of promoters of a north american trade bloc 
the united states canada and mexico need to form a common 
market to counter emerging freetrade zones in europe and asia say 
these boosters who count president bush among their numbers 
also supporters say it only makes sense for the united states 
to ease trade restrictions with its southern neighbor and 
thirdlargest trading partner mexico since it did so with its no 
1 partner canada two years ago 
following a usmexico agreement a north american freetrade 
zone could be created by a companion pact between canada and 
mexico an idea already backed by canadian officials 
that could mean products made in any one of the three nations 
could be freely sold in the other two creating a vast consumer 
market of more than 360 million people 
bush endorsed a north american common market in his presidential 
campaign two years ago he was in mexico on monday and tuesday for 
talks with president carlos salinas de gortari on establishing a 
usmexico freetrade pact the next step in creating such a 
trading zone 
supporters say such an accord would bring a number of benefits 
to americans including cheaper goods made by us companies in 
mexico an expanded market for us products in mexico and a 
counterbalance to the barrierfree europe planned by the end of 
1992 as well as moves by japan toward forming an asian trade bloc 
given the competition of the asian countries and japan 
especially the united states has to have access to cheaper labor 
in order to be able to compete internationally said abel 
beltrandelrio chief economist for ciemexwefa an economic 
consulting firm specializing in mexico 
for mexicans a pact should boost the nations troubled economy 
by luring us investment in plants and technology it also should 
open up the us market to more mexican products particularly 
agricultural goods boosters say 
for both countries a pact could ease friction over illegal 
mexican aliens in the united states 
supporters say there should be less reason for mexican laborers 
to migrate to the united states if there are more jobs at home in 
addition mexican officials want the pact to include provisions 
making it easier for mexicans to enter and work in this country 
despite these factors favoring a freetrade pact dont expect 
dutyfree tequila anytime soon detractors especially organized 
labor are expected to fiercely fight any agreement that could 
result in a weaker bargaining position for us workers and a loss 
of us factory jobs 
who gains from the agreement are us or multinational 
companies that can take advantage of very very low wages along 
with minimal environmental and workersafety rules in mexico said 
candice johnson a spokeswoman for the aflcio 
she said an idea of the outcome of a trade pact can be seen by 
examining the maquiladoras the thriving us assembly plants 
located just over the mexican border there mexican workers toil 
for as little as 290 a day under conditions resembling sweatshops 
of the late 19th and early 20th centuries the union coalition 
contends 
ms johnson said a north american freetrade agreement would be 
a disaster for us workers and ultimately canadian workers 
because everythings going to be made in mexico 
mexican officials and other boosters say any loss of us jobs 
would be offset by an increase in us exports to its southern 
neighbor 
for each incremental dollar mexico would receive through the 
pact about 15 cents would end up going to the united states 
through the purchase of us goods said edgardo mendoza valdes an 
official of the mexican stock brokerage probursa and a 
representative of the mexican financial sector to the trade talks 
under a freetrade agreement each nation would manufacture what 
it does best or cheapest he said 
there will be losses in some us sectors and there will be 
gains in other sectors from exporters said beltrandelrio the 
economist 
he also predicts us exports to the rest of the world would be 
boosted by the use of mexican labor bolstering the us economy 
i dont see why the united states cannot grow like it used to 
grow when its cost structure was more competitive in the world 
but mexico has its own critics of a freetrade agreement among 
their concerns is the sanctity of mexicos vast oil reserves 
nationalized in 1938 after accusations that us oil companies were 
exploiting the nation 
these critics dont want any freetrade pact to include the 
right for us oil companies to gain control of mexican oil fields 
since salinas took office in december 1988 mexico has lowered 
tariffs and joined the general agreement on trade and tariffs 
which his predecessors strongly opposed 
the united states shipped 2497 billion worth of goods to 
mexico in 1989 and imported 2719 billion in mexican goods for a 
us trade deficit with mexico of 22 billion 
