<TEXT>
the dun amp bradstreet corp said tuesday that it 
is no longer seeking buyers for two of its investment information 
subsidiaries datastream international and interactive data 
the company cited current conditions in financial markets 
worldwide for pulling the two companies off the sales block 
they generated a combined 155 million in revenue in 1989 and 
had been put up for sale in march as the company decided to shed 
some of its noncore businesses 
company spokesman reid gearhart declined to say whether there 
were any bids for the two companies or whether bids were too low 
he said dun amp bradstreet intended to continue to manage the 
companies at their current levels 
he noted that in the third quarter the parent company said 
datastream had generated higher revenue than a year ago while 
revenue was down at interactive data largely because of the 
termination of certain services that had been provided under 
previous owners 
datastream international based in london provides investment 
information principally on international securities interactive 
data based in lexington mass provides securitiesrelated 
information to the us investment community 
the two subsidiaries were among seven that dun amp bradstreet has 
put up for sale this year it has sold three of them while two 
others remain up for sale 
dun amp bradstreet is a world leader in marketing business 
information and related service with worldwide operating revenue of 
43 billion in 1989 
its companies provide the nielsen television audience ratings 
donnelley directory listings and moodys investors service credit 
reports 
