<TEXT>
confidence in the economy has sunk to levels 
near the depths of the 1982 recession and consumers are paring 
spending plans entering the christmas shopping season a survey 
released tuesday said 
the conference board said its survey of consumer confidence in 
november found more people expecting higher unemployment and weaker 
business conditions in the coming months 
fabian linden a conference board economist said consumer 
confidence has dropped to recession levels and is now only 
marginally above the figure recorded during the lowest point of the 
1982 economic downturn 
the business research organization said its monthly consumer 
confidence index continued to decline in november falling to 615 
from 626 in october 
the index which registered 1151 in november 1989 edged down 
as the economy has weakened earlier this year then tumbled after 
iraqs invasion of kuwait in august it stood at 1017 in july and 
then plunged to 847 in august 
the survey aso found consumers continued to scale back plans 
for major expenditures in november including cars appliances and 
vacations 
the conference boards survey results supported the predictions 
of economists and retail industry analysts who said consumers would 
spend less this christmas because of concerns about the economy and 
the middle east 
higher unemployment and higher prices for oil and other energy 
sources have left americans with less money to spend on what are 
called discretionary items clothing appliances furniture and 
gifts 
some retailers reported their holiday seasons began well but 
others found consumers were already cutting back their giftbuying 
sears roebuck and co the nations largest retailer said many 
shoppers appeared to be looking rather than buying over the 
thanksgiving day weekend and many appeared reluctant to commit 
themselves to big purchases sears said its sales were somewhat 
below expectations 
even smaller retailers and stores that sell toys and other 
merchandise popular this time of the year have been affected 
tonja little manager of the huggable hut a stuffedanimal shop 
in atlanta said tuesday that sales have fallen off sharply 
compared to last year at the same time 
people are coming in and looking but theyre not buying 
she said adding it has a lot to do with the economy slowing 
down 
sandra shaber an economist with the futures group in washington 
dc described the christmas season as off to a slow start 
she said it was not so much a lack of confidence that has made 
consumers hesitant but more a reflection of whats happened in 
the economy directly jobs have been lost since the summer and 
wages have not been keeping up with inflation 
elizabeth armstrong a retail industry analyst with prescott 
ball amp turben characterized christmas sales so far as mixed to 
somewhat disappointing she said warm weather in many parts of 
the country was another factor working against consumer spending 
the conference board survey found that americans have a dim view 
of the future of those asked 344 percent said there would be 
fewer jobs available in six months 97 percent said there would be 
more and 559 percent predicted employment would be the same 
when asked what business conditions would be like in six months 
112 percent said they would be better 295 said they would be 
worse and 593 said they would be the same 
the consumer confidence survey was conducted by national family 
opinion inc of toledo ohio which questioned 5000 households 
across the country the conference board is a businesssupported 
research group 
</TEXT>
