<DOCNO> AP901127-0230 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal bankruptcy judge tuesday granted 
eastern airlines a lifesaving 135 million infusion to keep it 
flying through winter and avoid repeated requests for money that 
have sapped public confidence in the carrier 
us bankruptcy judge burton r lifland said he approved the 
emergency request in part because of government statements that 
chaos could occur if eastern closes down during the holiday season 
eastern said it sought the money because bad publicity had 
worsened its financial outlook spooked potential passengers and 
made creditcard companies nervous about doing business with the 
carrier 
the emergency cash request from eastern was far more than it had 
anticipated asking for only a few weeks ago when the judge 
permitted the ailing airline to withdraw an immediate 15 million 
from an escrow fund at the time the judge said eastern could get 
another 15 million if it met certain cash projections as of dec 
3 
in the latest grant lifland went ahead and gave eastern the 15 
million plus 120 million more the judge placed 15 million in a 
contingency fund to be used if creditors demand the airline put up 
cash deposits before customers do business with it 
the money is intended to keep eastern alive through march 
avoiding the need for repeated requests for additional money 
under all these circumstances it seems inappropriate to 
constantly come back at these short intervals where the adverse 
publicity will be repeated again and again lifland said 
the judge also chastised the unsecured creditors committee for 
creating tension in easterns business through comments to the 
media that their goal is to close and liquidate the carrier he 
said the committees had a fiduciary duty to eastern 
easterns courtappointed trustee martin r shugrue jr 
praised the judge for giving eastern a vote of confidence 
the latest eastern request for cash fanned the anger of 
unsecured creditors who have been demanding that the court close 
down the airline which has been in financial distress since a 
crippling strike in march 1989 
a liquidation of eastern is inevitable creditor attorney 
joel b zweibel said in a court filing opposing the cash infusion 
it should begin now before further funds are wasted and while 
christmas holiday travelers have several weeks to rearrange their 
plans 
after the judge approved the request zweibel said creditors 
would meet to determine their next move 
shugrue said the airline needed to know that it would have 
access to a much larger supply of cash so it could make longterm 
plans 
we simply cannot run the business on a rolling 15day time 
frame he testified at the hearing in manhattans federal 
bankruptcy court 
shugrue said bad publicity from easterns previous requests for 
money caused passengers to shy away from the airline moreover he 
said credit card companies were starting to demand that the 
airline provide millions of dollars up front for charged tickets in 
case eastern goes out of business 
the unsecured creditors who are owed about 1 billion by the 
airline say eastern has virtually no chance of becoming a viable 
airline amid industrywide troubles brought on by higher fuel costs 
and sluggish demand for air travel 
shugrue has said eastern stands a good chance of reaching the 
breakeven point early next year through a marketing strategy that 
offers firstclass seats at coachclass prices 
but he told the judge tuesday that eastern not only needed the 
15 million lifland had agreed to release in early december but 
another 120 million to keep eastern operating through the first 
quarter of 1991 
eastern spokeswoman karen ceramsak said seeking money from the 
court a little at a time would lead to relentlessly bad publicity 
hinting that the airline was almost dead which could become a 
selffulfilling prophesy if travelers decide to fly with the 
competition so eastern decided to take a stab at getting operating 
funds through march at once ceremsak said 
we think its necessary to restore consumer confidence and 
build advance bookings she said we sustained significant 
damage as a result of the liquidation talk 
at the hearing earlier this month shugrue had told the judge 
that eastern would need a total of 80 million in a series of 
payments from the escrow fund through early january after that 
eastern did not believe it would need to tap any more cash from the 
fund and instead hoped to quickly repay the money he said 
but eastern officials said tuesday that talk of easterns 
possible liquidation cost it unforeseen cancellations and other 
problems that could cost 70 million 
miamibased eastern one of the industrys oldest and most 
troubled airlines filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection and 
reorganization march 9 1989 after unions crippled the airline 
with a strike 
the airline is now smaller than its prestrike size staffed 
with strike replacements and some unionists who returned to work 
but the machinists union remains on strike 
shugrue was appointed trustee last april after creditors lost 
faith in easterns management 
