<TEXT>
the big television networks are using the latest 
foreign buyout of a hollywood studio to bolster their effort to 
trash federal rules they say leave them at a disadvantage in the 
global entertainment market 
cbs abc and nbc each cited mondays announcement that japans 
matsushita electric industrial co had agreed to buy the american 
entertainment giant mca inc in a 66 billion deal as evidence 
that foreignowned companies have a head start on them in 
marshaling resources for quality programs 
the deal comes only three weeks before the federal 
communications commissions dec 14 hearing on the financial 
interest and syndication rules 
the 20yearold finsyn rules prohibit the three major tv 
networks from having financial interests in shows they dont own 
and from getting into the lucrative business of selling network 
programs in the 3 billion syndication market for reruns on local 
tv stations cable networks and foreign markets 
the rules have effectively barred the networks from bidding for 
production companies even as foreign companies have swooped in to 
buy four of the seven biggest us studios including three in the 
past 14 months 
laurence a tisch president and chief executive at cbs inc 
said the mca deal accelerates the dizzying pace of consolidation 
in hollywood 
this has happened under the financial interest rules that give 
foreignowned studios competitive advantages over the three 
american networks there is no more eloquent testimony for repeal 
of these rules than these transactions and the consolidation they 
have fostered he said 
sony corp of japan bought columbia pictures entertainment inc 
in september 1989 and italiancontrolled pathe communications corp 
recently completed a buyout of mgmua communications inc rupert 
murdochs news corp based in australia has owned 20th century 
fox corp since 1985 
there was some indication that policymakers in washington are 
hearing the networks complaints 
fcc chairman alfred sikes said the deal will almost certainly 
affect the debate and added the commission must consider the 
trend toward vertical integration in the entertainment business 
in concluding what restraints the networks should face if any in 
their efforts to integrate 
rep john dingell dmich chairman of the house energy and 
commerce committee which oversees the fcc and telecommunications 
policy said the mca deal is an event of considerable 
significance and said his committee would be interested to see 
what comes of the fcc examination of the finsyn rules 
entertainment is one of the few areas in which the us enjoys a 
trade surplus the congressman said 
our regulatory system should not protect foreignowned 
companies at the expense of american enterprise he said 
hollywood studios and producers support the rules because they 
fear that the networks as gatekeepers of the airwaves would 
have too much power if they could also have a stake in programs 
the three major national networks say whether a show goes on 
the air or not said jerry leider chairman of the caucus of 
independent writers producers and directors it doesnt make a 
difference whether mca is owned by a foreign interests or not 
he said without the finsyn rules the networks would soon 
dominate the production business by demanding concessions on 
syndication sales from producers trying to get a show on the 
network 
but the networks argue their power over programming has been 
diluted by the proliferation of alternatives such as independent tv 
stations and cable tv 
richard cotton general counsel for the national broadcasting 
co said the mca deal leaves only three major usowned hollywood 
studio companies paramount communications inc walt disney co 
and time warner inc 
the great irony in this development is that us regulatory 
policy is actually contributing to the demise of us 
competitiveness in the global entertainment sector cotton said 
at capital citiesabc inc spokeswoman julie hoover said the 
deal showed the anachronism of rules that prevent the three 
domestic network companies from competing effectively in the global 
and domestic environment 
leider who was cochairman of the committee representing the 
studios and producers in unsuccessful talks with the networks last 
summer over changes in the finsyn rules said he expects the rules 
will be modified 
we have an an enlightened fcc that sees the wisdom of 
safeguards he said i dont think chairman sikes has indicated 
in that statement that the rules will be repealed 
</TEXT>
