<TEXT>
the 22 billion point arguello offshore 
oil facility which has been dormant since its completion two years 
ago will begin pumping crude within a few months chevron corp 
announced tuesday 
the san franciscobased company the largest of 18 partners in 
the project also said it would build a new multimillion dollar 
underground pipeline to ship oil to refineries in the los angeles 
area completion of that project would take at least three chevron 
spokesman mike libbey said 
the point arguello project is about 10 miles off point 
conception which is about 150 miles northwest of los angeles 
the consortium wants to ship heavy crude via doublehulled 
vessels to refineries in the los angeles area however santa 
barbara county officials on nov 12 rejected a proposal by the us 
department of energy to use tankers for interim hauling of 40000 
barrels daily while a pipeline was being built 
the consortium then decided to begin producing 20000 barrels 
per day and send it to northern california via the allamerican 
pipeline which needs a fivemile connection to a unocal refinery 
near santa maria libbey said 
unocal would use about 10000 to 15000 barrels per day and the 
remainder will be shipped to refineries in the bakersfield area or 
in contra costa county near san francisco he said 
the ultimate preferred destination is los angeles because 
thats where the need is its the biggest gasoline market in 
the world libbey said 
he also said the company preferred to transport the highsulfer 
or sour crude via pipeline not tanker but that the consortium 
would still push for using ships while the los angeles pipeline was 
being built 
an appeal of the santa barbara county decision was filed tuesday 
with the california coastal commission he said and a hearing is 
expected within a few months 
point arguello is permitted to produce up to 100000 barrels of 
heavy crude per day 
the project was built in the early 1980s on the assumption that 
oil prices would be between 40 and 80 per barrel earlier this 
year when oil prices dropped below 20 per barrel chevron 
officials said the partners would have lost money on every barrel 
produced and the company took a 445 million writedown against 
its fourthquarter 1989 profits 
however chevron officials said that bringing in any amount of 
cash from the point arguello project would help defray its costs 
</TEXT>
